        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780375752193" href="/book/show/9484.Within_a_Budding_Grove">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer67021563" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer693393259641329281"><i>the review is missing. <br/>below are the comments which followed.</i><br/><br/><br/><b>David</b> – You’re wrong that this is better than <i>Swann’s Way</i> and you’re wrong in calling Proust an ‘anti-romantic’. Try again, jewtard!<br/><br/><br/><b>Brian</b> – read more carefully, gothskimmer. i wrote that ‘one could say’ that proust was anti-romantic. all i mean is that his extreme nuerosis and need to analyze everything (to death!) kinda reduces every creature to a &apos;thinking machine&apos;. after hundreds of pages of his wildly in-depth analysis i don’t feel</span>
  <span id="freeText693393259641329281" style="display:none"><i>the review is missing. <br>below are the comments which followed.</i><br><br><br><b>David</b> – You’re wrong that this is better than <i>Swann’s Way</i> and you’re wrong in calling Proust an ‘anti-romantic’. Try again, jewtard!<br><br><br><b>Brian</b> – read more carefully, gothskimmer. i wrote that ‘one could say’ that proust was anti-romantic. all i mean is that his extreme nuerosis and need to analyze everything (to death!) kinda reduces every creature to a 'thinking machine'. after hundreds of pages of his wildly in-depth analysis i don’t feel that <i>In Search of Lost Time</i> is, as the translator blurbs, ‘marvelously about life’, but more that man is a fleshy robot in which synapses jump around causing all kinds of different actions and reactions. <br><br><br><b>David</b> – Although I know you’d love a steel phallus jammed up your jewhole, robots don’t love. <br><br><br><b>Brian</b> – agreed. but even upon first meeting albertine, marcel writes <br><br><i>“…I had hesitated a long time between her and her friends, that quite as much as with her I had contemplated falling in love Albertine, with the girl with bright eyes, with Rosemonde.”</i> <br><br>marcel may feel love and wonder and mystery and may enjoy drunkenness or watching a band of girls misbehave or bergotte’s books or elstir’s paintings, but at a certain point one feels the author merely charts the movement of his character’s brain much like a surgeon reads a CAT scan… he openly acknowledges that he could love <i>any</i> of them, thus stripping love of its unique and mystical qualities. <br><br><br><b>David</b> – You’re misreading it and not probing deep enough, rothstooge. What he means is that he knows that being the sensitive, analytical, love-starved manwhore that he is, he could easily fall in love with any of these women. He's commenting on his own insecurities not on the women or on love. Also that what might start out as mystery or attraction could blossom into true love. Kind of what Donald hopes for here on goodreads. <br><br><br><b>Donald</b> – At least I’m after women, buttercup. You and Gottlieb can eat a bag of shit, curl up together, and read Proust to the sweet sounds of Morrissey in the background.<br><br><br><b>Matthew</b> – HAHA!<br><br><br><b>David</b> – Gotti has taste, Donald. So when we spoon (I’m the top, gotti!) he <i>will</i> be reading Proust. You and Matthew can share tales of elfin lore and rainbow-farting unicorns. <br><br><br><b>MFSO</b> – Elves and unicorns are every bit as real as an invisible sky god. <br><br><br><b>Books Ring My Bell</b> – I wish I could fart rainbows. I’d still want them to smell like shit but I wish they looked like rainbows. <br><br><br><b>Karen</b> – Rainbow-farting unicorns are diiiiiiirrrrrrrrrty. <br><br><br><b>Brian</b> – i think we were all waiting for that.<br><br><br><b>Montambo</b> – Even unicorns who fart are cute! <br><br><br><b>Matthew</b> – I don’t like books about elves and unicorns! HAHA!<br><br><br><b>Tosh</b> – I’m sure Boris Vian influenced by Proust. He is a super-duper rock star! <br><br><br><b>David E.</b> – Essential reading. It was rumored that when Candy Darling was found dead, she was holding a semen-stained copy of <i>The Guermantes Way</i> in her arms. <br><br><br><b>J. Treat</b> – I never heard that, David… that’s v. interesting… <br><br><br><b>Ben</b> - Agreed, Chairy! RAWRRRR!!! <br><br><br><b>Michelle</b> – <span>[image error]</span><br><br><br><b>Brian</b> – my particular form of OCD totally locks into proust’s writing: i’m too much in my head, i over-analyze EVERYTHING, i come at everything from a million angles over and over and over. as does proust. it’s strange: he writes a 730 page book about a weak, snobby guy taking a seaside vacation hoping to fall in love. what should be breezy and light and incredibly irritating ends up being anything but -- it’s almost as clashing and unexpected as if mitch albom were to re-write <i>the brothers karamazov</i> and it was better than the original. so i do agree with you, david – proust is incredibly romantic. the obvious analogy: only when one looks from far away at a Seurat painting does it make sense; up close it’s just a bunch of dots... proust kinda does that: from far away, society makes sense, but up close we’re all just a bunch of dots. it’s an unsettling feeling and i kind of love it. <br><br><br><b>Ben Harrison</b> – ‘all just a bunch of dots’. Like what Harry Lime calls people in Graham Greene’s <i>The Third Man</i>. <br><br><br><b>Gary</b> – LOL BUDDY!!!!!!!!! The Third Man is great book!!!!!! So FUNNY! I had tearsrollong down my eyes!!!!!!!!!!!<br><br><br><b>David</b> - <i>'I do agree with you, david'</i>. <br><br>Of course you do, sweetheart. <br><br><br><b>Gary</b> – What??? I don’t agree with DACId. Why did he write this!!!<br><br><br><b>Donald</b> – He wasn’t responding to you, Gary. He was responding to Brian. <br><br><br><b>Gary</b> – LOL!!!!!!<br><br><br><b>Chris</b> – I hate Mitch Albom.<br><br><br><b>Matt</b> – HAHA!<br><br><br><b>Sarah</b>– <i>'after reading the first two volumes i find that proust is just how i thought he’d be. but like a 12 yr old boy imagining a blowjob, he can understand, technically, what it is and have an idea of how it’ll feel… but one can never really know what a blowjob is like until that instant in which someone closes their lips around your shaft.'</i><br><br>Brian, I always love a good blowjob comparison and I’m sure Proust wouldn’t mind, but you really went a little far on this one. <br> <br><br><b>David</b> – Ignore him , Sarah. That’s just one in a series of repeated attempts to transcend his white Jewish middle-class suburban youth by a campaign of linguistic shock and awe.<br><br><br><b>Sarah</b> – And where you wrote ‘shaft’… I don’t stop till I hit ‘base’, honey. <br><br><br><b>Matthew</b> – HAHA!<br><br><br><b>Mike Reynolds</b> –There is merit and accuracy in both Brian and David's arguments and it is exactly these tensions and contradictions that makes Proust great. As Brian pointed out he is breezy and light but writes about subjects as heavy as did the Russians; he is a snob but able to see outside his social class enough to make us care about the French aristocracy. Proust is both a 'romantic' and 'anti-romantic': he values love and life and art above all else but does - in depicting the 'OCD' (as Brian puts it) involved in manners, etiquette, and in his own exhausting mental processes - reduce humans to their most base and animal instincts.<br><br><br><b>Donald</b> – Nice Mike. <br><br><br><b>Brian</b> – i wanna wash your balls, mike. <br><br><br><b>David</b> – Stop kissing ass, Donald. <br><br><br><b>Isaiah</b> – I loathe hipsters. <br><br><br><b>Shelly</b> – But you <i>are</i> a hipster. <br><br><br><b>Jen</b> – I am Gary! AAAAAHHHHHHH!!!!!<br><br><br><b>Gary</b> – Someone is say they are me!!! Somone posts my name!!!!<br><br><br><b>Jen</b> – LOL!!!!!!!!</span>
